1
00:00:02,000 --> 00:00:07,302
If you've ever run a mean-variance optimizer and gotten portfolio

2
00:00:07,402 --> 00:00:11,458
weights like 120% in one asset and negative 80% in

3
00:00:11,558 --> 00:00:17,692
another, you've experienced the input sensitivity problem of classical MVO.

4
00:00:17,783 --> 00:00:21,879
In 1990, Goldman Sachs researchers Fischer Black and

5
00:00:21,979 --> 00:00:25,914
Robert Litterman published the fix. It changed how

6
00:00:26,014 --> 00:00:30,595
institutional portfolio managers build portfolios forever.

7
00:00:33,183 --> 00:00:36,640
Black-Litterman combines a Bayesian prior — the

8
00:00:36,740 --> 00:00:39,971
market equilibrium — with your active views.

9
00:00:40,066 --> 00:00:45,889
Using matrix algebra, it produces stable, intuitive portfolio weights.

10
00:00:45,989 --> 00:00:49,866
The genius is in the starting point: instead of

11
00:00:49,966 --> 00:00:54,942
guessing expected returns — which causes all the instability

12
00:00:55,042 --> 00:00:59,934
— you reverse-engineer what the market is already implying.

13
00:01:02,533 --> 00:01:08,086
Start with market-cap weights. The market equilibrium implies these weights

14
00:01:08,186 --> 00:01:12,609
are optimal for some aggregate level of risk aversion delta.

15
00:01:12,700 --> 00:01:17,975
Reverse-engineer the implied expected returns: pi equals delta times

16
00:01:18,075 --> 00:01:22,481
the covariance matrix times the market-cap weights. Pi is

17
00:01:22,581 --> 00:01:26,276
your prior — the market's best guess of expected

18
00:01:26,376 --> 00:01:31,256
returns, reflected in current prices. It's the neutral starting

19
00:01:31,356 --> 00:01:34,656
point before you add any views of your own.

20
00:01:37,250 --> 00:01:41,489
Suppose you have K views. Each view is expressed

21
00:01:41,589 --> 00:01:45,286
as P times mu equals q plus epsilon-views.

22
00:01:45,383 --> 00:01:50,261
P is a K by N pick matrix describing which assets your view

23
00:01:50,361 --> 00:01:56,504
is about. Q is the vector of view returns. Omega captures your uncertainty

24
00:01:56,604 --> 00:02:01,651
in each view — the smaller omega, the more confident you are.

25
00:02:01,750 --> 00:02:07,691
Concrete example: you believe US Tech will outperform EU Banks

26
00:02:07,791 --> 00:02:12,174
by 3% annually. P has plus-one for US Tech and

27
00:02:12,274 --> 00:02:18,021
minus-one for EU Banks. Q equals 0.03. Omega-one-one is your

28
00:02:18,121 --> 00:02:24,258
uncertainty squared — your confidence in this specific forecast.

29
00:02:26,850 --> 00:02:30,638
Combine the prior and views using Bayes' theorem. The

30
00:02:30,738 --> 00:02:35,700
Black-Litterman posterior mean is this formula — a precision-weighted

31
00:02:35,800 --> 00:02:38,342
average of the prior and your views.

32
00:02:38,950 --> 00:02:43,751
Tau is a scalar expressing how uncertain you are

33
00:02:43,851 --> 00:02:49,266
about the prior. Typically set between 0.025 and 0.05.

34
00:02:49,350 --> 00:02:52,877
High confidence views — small omega — pull the

35
00:02:52,977 --> 00:02:58,239
posterior strongly toward your forecast. Low confidence views barely

36
00:02:58,339 --> 00:03:02,498
move it from equilibrium. This is exactly the Bayesian

37
00:03:02,598 --> 00:03:05,810
behaviour you want from a portfolio model.

38
00:03:10,400 --> 00:03:15,096
Plug the BL posterior into the standard mean-variance optimizer.

39
00:03:15,196 --> 00:03:18,468
Here in blue are the market-cap weights — the

40
00:03:18,568 --> 00:03:21,916
neutral starting point when you have no views.

41
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:26,632
In teal are the BL weights after expressing the view that

42
00:03:26,732 --> 00:03:32,527
US equities will outperform. The optimizer tilts toward US equities and

43
00:03:32,627 --> 00:03:37,259
away from EU — in exact proportion to your confidence. No

44
00:03:37,359 --> 00:03:42,324
extreme positions. No corner solutions from estimation noise.

45
00:03:42,416 --> 00:03:47,588
The practical result: BL portfolios look like real portfolios

46
00:03:47,688 --> 00:03:52,515
— diversified, intuitive, tilted in the direction of your

47
00:03:52,615 --> 00:03:57,700
convictions rather than dominated by optimization artifacts.

48
00:04:00,300 --> 00:04:06,635
Common abuse one: setting tau incorrectly. Many practitioners default tau to

49
00:04:06,735 --> 00:04:11,886
1, which makes the prior too uncertain and lets views dominate

50
00:04:11,986 --> 00:04:16,544
— reintroducing the instability BL was designed to fix.

51
00:04:16,633 --> 00:04:21,820
Common abuse two: treating omega as diagonal. This assumes view

52
00:04:21,920 --> 00:04:27,024
errors are uncorrelated — fine if views are truly independent,

53
00:04:27,124 --> 00:04:30,885
but wrong if they share a common macro driver.

54
00:04:30,983 --> 00:04:37,165
Common abuse three: using only absolute views. Absolute views are harder to

55
00:04:37,265 --> 00:04:43,028
calibrate and more sensitive to error. Prefer relative views — asset A

56
00:04:43,128 --> 00:04:47,803
beats B by X percent — which are more natural and stable.

57
00:04:50,400 --> 00:04:55,496
BL maps directly to DeFi yield optimization. The equilibrium

58
00:04:55,596 --> 00:05:00,260
prior is the current yield allocation across protocols.

59
00:05:00,350 --> 00:05:08,148
Your views are protocol-specific forecasts. For example: Aave's utilization

60
00:05:08,248 --> 00:05:13,202
will increase by 15%, boosting supply APY by 2%.

61
00:05:13,302 --> 00:05:17,941
Or: Curve's CRV incentives will be cut in the

62
00:05:18,041 --> 00:05:22,786
next governance vote, reducing pool APY by 3%.

63
00:05:22,883 --> 00:05:27,052
These views are expressed in the P matrix, and BL blends

64
00:05:27,152 --> 00:05:33,228
them with the equilibrium yield allocation to produce stable reallocation weights

65
00:05:33,328 --> 00:05:37,879
— without the extreme positions classical MVO would generate.

66
00:05:39,466 --> 00:05:44,694
The key insight of BL: start from the market, not from guesses.

67
00:05:44,783 --> 00:05:48,975
When you have no view, hold the market. When you have a

68
00:05:49,075 --> 00:05:55,373
view, tilt proportionally to your confidence. When you have strong conviction, set

69
00:05:55,473 --> 00:05:59,275
a small omega and let the view move the posterior.

70
00:05:59,366 --> 00:06:03,206
The formula ensures your views are incorporated in a

71
00:06:03,306 --> 00:06:08,434
mathematically coherent way that classical MVO simply cannot achieve.

